OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F371A1779894668
OL,3,CHow to get your kids to listen and
OL,4,Cwant to do what you say
OL,6,FA useful consideration in our
OL,7,Fcommunication with anyone is to
OL,8,Fconsider 'what is their why?' What
OL,9,Fwould they want to do? And ideally,
OL,10,Fhelping people shift from 'I have to'
OL,11,Fto 'I want to'.
OL,13,FHere are some tips that can help with
OL,14,Fthat process:
OL,16,F1. Ask a child what they already know
OL,18,FInstead of telling a child
OL,19,Finformation, which they might already
OL,20,Fknow anyway, ask them about the topic.
OL,1,W~+$ ~sh7}h7sj5 ~{4~k4k4          G2/8
OL,2,W+.! +,*%/"-'"-$/*%/*%/.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BC Eng News CThis Day FReg TV
FL,372,370,120,260,000,100
PN,37103
SC,0003
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F371A1779894668
OL,3,CHow to get your kids to listen and
OL,4,Cwant to do what you say
OL,6,FFor example, 'What do you know about
OL,7,Fwhat can happen if you cycle without
OL,8,Fyour helmet?' This helps to engage
OL,9,Fthem in the conversation and raise
OL,10,Fthat all important autonomy that
OL,11,Fchildren need.
OL,13,F2. Present options and choices
OL,15,FFor example, instead of saying 'Eat
OL,16,Fyour veg please', we might say, 'It's
OL,17,Fimportant that you eat your veg. Would
OL,18,Fyou like to try the peas or the
OL,19,Fcarrots first?'
OL,21,F3. Introduce fun and gameplay
OL,1,W~+$ ~sh7}h7sj5 ~{4~k4k4          G3/8
OL,2,W+.! +,*%/"-'"-$/*%/*%/.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BC Eng News CThis Day FReg TV
